From: philipr@extro.ucc.su.OZ.AU (Philip Rhoades)
Subject: Re: Auf English: Linux /cv -- Linux commercial version.
Date: Sun, 14 Nov 1993 04:02:25 GMT

kris@toppoint.de (Kristian Koehntopp) writes:

>[ Moderator's note: this is an English translation of the German
>  announcement posted recently.  --liw ]


>The Free Software Association of Germany is happy to announce the
>following:

>1) Linux-Support

>Starting now, we guarantee all commericial Linux users
>free support.  The free support is restricted to hotline,
>fax or e-mail.  The support can only be used, when the
>applications software (also of commercial nature) has
>been ported to the Linux Operating System and the company
>has their headquarters in the European Community. 


>The main purpose of our organization is the development
>and distribution of so-called "Free" software.  So that
>in the future we no longer have to choose only between
>"Windows" and "Windows", with Linux /CV we are trying to
>present a universal and functional OS that can serve the
>hobbyist, as well and the commercial user. 


>Linux /cv is in no way "only" a new distribution.  It
>contains all features that a commercial system
>should contain. 


>  + Simple and pre-configured installation
>  + Manuals and hypertext-like Help Databaes
>  + Hotline and commercial support, also with guaranteed Reaction  
>Time
>  + Tested hardware compatability list
>  + Commercial Products (For Examples, OSF Motif) already integrated

>Linux /CV starts the the 99.PL13 kernel.  It will be
>brought to the current Linux update status a maximum of
>two times per year.  All programs that are still in the
>Alpha-Stage (wine, dosemu, elf, etc) will not be
>integrated.  We have completely debugged Linux /CV and
>made changes, so it (the kernel) can no longer be upgraded
>with "official" patches. 

Why will it not diverge to a completely different product if it can't be 
updated with "official" patches? Is there any intention to head towards 
compliability with X/Open's UNIX?

