From: rick@sundance.SJSU.EDU (Richard Warner)
Subject: Re: free X things, was Re: WD8003_w_telnet
Date: 14 Nov 93 16:03:34 GMT

camerons@NAD.3Com.COM (Cameron Spitzer) writes:

>In article 753036100@pv3440.vincent.iastate.edu, werdna@iastate.edu (Andrew J. Albinger) writes:
>>In <2btnn1$nh@rubb.rz.ruhr-uni-bochum.de> ruediger@tau.ep1.ruhr-uni-bochum.de (Ruediger Berlich) writes:

>>>Which other free telnet-programs are there or does there exist even a *free*
>>>port of X to the MS-Windows-architecture (Allow X-windows from another host
>>>to open a window on your desktop) ?

>>there are no "free" x things for the pc.  There are some nice ways of doing
>>what you want using pctcp but that will cost $$$

>I've been running XFree86-1.3 since the summer.
>XFree86 is free.  It's a port of The X Window System (X11R5),
>which is also free, and runs on all the 386 un*xes I can
>think of, including Linux and FreeBSD, which are free.
>(Is it stable?  It's been running continuously for about eighty
>days now.  I run a tiny Usenet site.)
>Linux' TCP/IP still needs work, but people are using it.

>There may be no "free x things" for MSWindows, but there are lots
>of great free X things for IBM-PC-compatibles.

This seems to be a popular comeback.  But let's face it  - LINUX is a hacker's
toy and is great for a small segment of the population that is willing
and able to devote the time, energy, and money to getting it to work.  For
that small segment of the population, XFree is a good thing.   Also, let's
get one thing straight.  LINUX and XFree are not 'free' - minimum cost
of putting this combination on a PC is $75 for hardware (you really need
100 Mb of disk space, and current prices are $.75/Mb), but can be much
greater if your hardware needs to be upgraded to comply with the narrow
range of options supported under this environment.  We could also add in
the cost of the dowload time+diskettes or the CD-ROM, but that varies
all over the map so I won't bother.

For the remaining 95%+ of the PC market segment, XFree is a non-viable
option.  These folks need to run off-the-shelf, supported software and
do not have either the time or the expertise to mess around with the
free UNIX variants like LINUX, etc.   For these folks this comeback is
a slap in the face, not a constructive answer.

So, let's phrase an answer for these folks.  There is no such thing as
a free X-server software for mainstream, commercial, vendor supported 
PC operating environments.  For those who need/desire to run one of
these machines, there are commercially available X server products at
prices ranging from moderate to expensive.

For DOS or as a DOS client under MS-Windows, the least expensive option 
at the moment is X-Kit from XLink Technologies (Milpitas, CA). Current
price is $199 (including TCP/IP), or $135 for educational groups.  GraphPoint
in Cupertino, CA also has a low price entry, running in the <$200 range,
including TCP/IP.  GraphPoint has the advantage of having separate DOS
and Windows packages, and has the disadvantage of being a 16-bit implementation
(X-Kit is 32-bit).

For serial line only connections, NCD and Hummingbird have packages at
about $150 each for PC's running DOS/MS-Windows.  

For educational groups, DesqView/X value pack is $125/200 (DesqView/X,
QEMM, Network Manager, and LAN WorkPlace for DOS) [first 5 copies are
$125, then $200 for each additional copy].

For OS/2 users, IBM has a TCP/IP base product with an X add-in.  Total
price for the latest version is around $350-400.

There are numerous other options; anyone interested should check out the
X Journal or UNIX World to see the wealth of available options.

>Cameron in Santa Clara

