From: root@belvedere.sbay.org (David E. Fox)
Subject: Re: HELP - Linux counter moral issue
Date: Sun, 14 Nov 1993 03:47:17 GMT

Harald T. Alvestrand (hta@uninett.no) wrote:
: Hello,
: I have a "moral" problem regarding the Linux counter.

: I have had some exchanges with a particular sitemaster that
: wanted to register 500 Linux users at that site.

: - Ignore it, and let the votes be counted
: - Delete all votes from this site, keeping the statistics as they are,
:   but not gathering the information

I wouldn't necessarily consider 500 users at a particular site running Linux
as 500 separate users.  In my opinion, a user of linux is a person with
a machine running linux, either at home, or at work.  A guest on a dial-up
Linux site doesn't equate in my mind to a Linux user, at least for
vote-counting purposes, since the object of this vote-counting (unless
I'm confused) is supposed to count the number of installed linux systems.

Furthermore, if the site is on the internet, there could be several folks
in their passwd file who telnet from other sites, and could possibly
be running linux from any one of a number of systems, and that would 
be like voting twice (or more) in my opinion.

: BTW, the current count (including perhaps half the 500 users) is now
: about 3.700 users.

This becomes more important since the number of potential votes (depending
on what you choose to do) is such a large percentage of votes you've
already counted.

   
